  "n_features": 102,
  "analysis": "The best configuration is LightGBM with is_unbalance=True, n_estimators=350, max_depth=7, lr=0.05, num_leaves=50, min_child_samples=5, using all 102 features. The key breakthrough was using LightGBM's is_unbalance=True flag to handle the 4:1 genuine/impostor class imbalance. The most discriminative feature is scr_std (scroll speed standard deviation), followed by keystroke interval shape statistics (ksi_kurt, ksi_skew) and typing speed (derived_chars_per_sec). All five feature groups are necessary — removing any group increases EER. LightGBM outperforms Random Forest (best baseline at 0.3285), XGBoost, Gradient Boosting, SVM, and Isolation Forest on this dataset. The remaining EER of ~0.32 reflects dataset limitations: small per-user sample sizes (25 sessions/user), session-level aggregation losing temporal dynamics, and a global classifier rather than per-user enrollment models. Optimal hyperparameters: 350 trees (sweep from 200-1000 confirmed 350 as sweet spot at lr=0.05), 50 leaves (vs. 15-63), depth=7 (vs. 5-9), lr=0.05 (vs. 0.02-0.10). Regularization (L1/L2) and subsampling both hurt — suggesting the features are clean and informative without over-fitting risk at this model complexity.",
